Anyways, if you’ve ever had a cat one thing
you know about cats is they don’t like to

01:17:29.020 --> 01:17:30.020
move.

01:17:30.020 --> 01:17:33.020
It makes them very upset and nervous, and
if you put them in a new house they’re not

01:17:33.020 --> 01:17:34.210
happy about it.

01:17:34.210 --> 01:17:37.230
The reason for that is you’ve blown their
map, right?

01:17:37.230 --> 01:17:42.810
The cat will slink around in a new territory
and map every single place and every hiding

01:17:42.810 --> 01:17:47.880
place, obsessively, until it knows what the
hell’s going on, and then it will finally

01:17:47.880 --> 01:17:48.880
relax.

01:17:48.880 --> 01:17:51.040
A cat in a new place is not a calm cat.

01:17:51.040 --> 01:17:56.460
A cat in a new place is a nervous cat, which
is also an indication that you don’t have

01:17:56.460 --> 01:17:58.480
to learn to be afraid.

01:17:58.480 --> 01:18:00.910
What you have to learn is how to be calm.

01:18:00.910 --> 01:18:05.300
That reverse the way that psychologists generally
talk about anxiety, because they’re all

01:18:05.300 --> 01:18:08.090
hobbits and they think that life is safe.

01:18:08.090 --> 01:18:11.770
So because they think that life is safe, you
have to learn to be afraid.

01:18:11.770 --> 01:18:13.220
That’s dopey.

01:18:13.220 --> 01:18:16.631
The natural condition is terror and curiosity.

01:18:16.631 --> 01:18:20.350
If you’re really lucky now and then, you’re
somewhere safe enough so that you don’t

01:18:20.350 --> 01:18:21.930
have to be afraid.

01:18:21.930 --> 01:18:24.730
That’s tenuous and delicate.

01:18:24.730 --> 01:18:27.170
So what you have to learn is how not to be
afraid.

01:18:27.170 --> 01:18:29.090
Not, how to be afraid.

01:18:29.090 --> 01:18:31.820
Anyways, they got the cat.

01:18:31.820 --> 01:18:36.260
So he’s in his box and they take him out
of the box and the cat thinks, “so this

01:18:36.260 --> 01:18:37.260
is the country.”

01:18:37.260 --> 01:18:42.520
So the cat goes really low and starts sniffing,
and that is what animals do when they first

01:18:42.520 --> 01:18:43.590
start exploring.

01:18:43.590 --> 01:18:48.750
Both of those things: they crouch down because
that makes them less visible to predators,

01:18:48.750 --> 01:18:49.750
and they sniff.

01:18:49.750 --> 01:18:56.239
The reason they sniff is because most animals
have their whole brains built around their

01:18:56.239 --> 01:19:00.670
sense of smell; unlike us, where most of our
brain is built around vision.

01:19:00.670 --> 01:19:05.780
Anyways, the cat’s slinking around there
and it smells something that it doesn’t

01:19:05.780 --> 01:19:06.780
know.

01:19:06.780 --> 01:19:11.050
It thinks, God only knows what this thing
that I don’t know is.

01:19:11.050 --> 01:19:14.700
It would freeze first and then it would hastily
retreat.

01:19:14.700 --> 01:19:16.920
So now it’s underneath the porch.

01:19:16.920 --> 01:19:19.350
One hippie says, “where’d the cat disappear
now?”

01:19:19.350 --> 01:19:21.130
The other one says, “under the house.”

01:19:21.130 --> 01:19:26.000
The cat’s down there shaking, which is what
cats do when they’re freaked out like that,

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:28.360
and it’s got it’s little fantasy going.

01:19:28.360 --> 01:19:30.520
You’d hide to if you smelled what I did.

01:19:30.520 --> 01:19:32.370
Then it imagines up this monster.

01:19:32.370 --> 01:19:36.900
A monster technically is the amalgamation
of unrelated parts.

01:19:36.900 --> 01:19:38.420
So what’s the monster?

01:19:38.420 --> 01:19:44.840
Well its got duck feet and bare arms and its
got a skunk tail and its got kind of a wolf

01:19:44.840 --> 01:19:46.060
head, and its got antlers.

01:19:46.060 --> 01:19:49.160
You think, well that thing doesn’t exist.

01:19:49.160 --> 01:19:50.430
That’s wrong.

01:19:50.430 --> 01:19:51.430
That thing exists.

01:19:51.430 --> 01:19:56.710
In fact it’s a really accurate representation
of what’s out there in the forest.

01:19:56.710 --> 01:20:01.840
Any one animal wouldn’t look like that,
but the set of all possible animals looks

01:20:01.840 --> 01:20:03.050
exactly like that.

01:20:03.050 --> 01:20:08.420
Then you might think, well what do you want
first, when you’re analyzing something?

01:20:08.420 --> 01:20:12.220
Do you want quick and dirty representation
of what to be afraid of?

01:20:12.220 --> 01:20:15.860
Or do you want to hang around trying to figure
out whether that thing has hooves and teeth?

01:20:15.860 --> 01:20:21.190
It’s like no, you want a quick and dirty
representation of just what might be lurking

01:20:21.190 --> 01:20:22.430
out there.

01:20:22.430 --> 01:20:24.530
That’s intelligent hypothesizing.

01:20:24.530 --> 01:20:28.030
It’s the kind of hypothesizing that would
be evolutionary driven.

01:20:28.030 --> 01:20:33.340
Did you ever see the far side cartoon, Monster
Snorkel?

01:20:33.340 --> 01:20:35.390
I love that cartoon.

01:20:35.390 --> 01:20:40.770
There’s this little kid in his bed, it’s
dark and he’s under cover.

01:20:40.770 --> 01:20:44.350
He’s one of those ugly little kids that
Gary Larson always drew.

01:20:44.350 --> 01:20:51.030
He’s got this snorkel that you use for scuba
diving.

01:20:51.030 --> 01:20:54.450
Snorkeling, not scuba diving.

01:20:54.450 --> 01:20:59.360
All that’s sticking out from under the covers
is his snorkel so that he can breathe.

01:20:59.360 --> 01:21:05.940
Of course in his imagination there’s some
reptilian dinosaur sitting beside his bed.

01:21:05.940 --> 01:21:07.210
Well, why?

01:21:07.210 --> 01:21:09.750
That’s what he’s hypothesizing.

01:21:09.750 --> 01:21:10.750
Why?

01:21:10.750 --> 01:21:14.000
Because that’s what’s in the dark.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:17.800
You can tell your kid, there’s no monsters
in the dark.

01:21:17.800 --> 01:21:19.989
Then you tell your kid to never talk to a
stranger.

01:21:19.989 --> 01:21:21.870
Well get your story straight people.

01:21:21.870 --> 01:21:22.870
Really?

01:21:22.870 --> 01:21:24.210
It’s so dopey.

01:21:24.210 --> 01:21:27.260
Yes there are monsters in the dark.

01:21:27.260 --> 01:21:28.260
What do you tell your kids?

01:21:28.260 --> 01:21:30.040
No, there’s no such thing as monsters.

01:21:30.040 --> 01:21:35.210
First of all they’re driven half crazy because
they think what am I afraid of then?

01:21:35.210 --> 01:21:39.380
Second, you tell them all of the time that
there are monsters in the dark.

01:21:39.380 --> 01:21:43.870
In fact you’re probably more paranoid about
the things than your damn kid is.

01:21:43.870 --> 01:21:45.060
So what do you tell them?

01:21:45.060 --> 01:21:49.330
There are monsters in the dark but you can
probably handle them, especially with our

01:21:49.330 --> 01:21:50.330
help.

01:21:50.330 --> 01:21:52.750
Okay, so now I’ll tell you a story.

01:21:52.750 --> 01:22:00.670
So my nephew, he was six, and he had night
terrors.

01:22:00.670 --> 01:22:04.780
Night terrors are this strange phenomena where
all of a sudden you wake up screaming.

01:22:04.780 --> 01:22:07.500
It’s quite unpleasant.

01:22:07.500 --> 01:22:09.600
You might say, well why is this happening?

01:22:09.600 --> 01:22:13.770
The answer is that we really don’t know
but there was some instability in his household

01:22:13.770 --> 01:22:14.770
at that point.

01:22:14.770 --> 01:22:18.370
A, he was just going off to kindergarten,
so that’s a big transition.

01:22:18.370 --> 01:22:21.130
It’s out of paradise and out into the world.

01:22:21.130 --> 01:22:27.250
B, his parents were in the throws of approaching
divorce, so there was that sort of undercurrent

01:22:27.250 --> 01:22:28.250
in the house.

01:22:28.250 --> 01:22:29.610
You know what that’s like.

01:22:29.610 --> 01:22:32.710
You walk into a house like that and you know
something’s up.

01:22:32.710 --> 01:22:34.440
It’s like the air is frozen.

01:22:34.440 --> 01:22:37.800
It’s probably something you can smell, I
think.

01:22:37.800 --> 01:22:41.510
Whatever, it doesn’t matter, but you can
certainly tell.

01:22:41.510 --> 01:22:44.560
So anyways, he’s waking up at night screaming
away.

01:22:44.560 --> 01:22:47.210
He’s a very verbal kid.

01:22:47.210 --> 01:22:51.300
During the day he’s running around, I guess
he was about four, not six.

01:22:51.300 --> 01:22:53.530
He’s got this little night hat that he wears.

01:22:53.530 --> 01:22:54.650
It’s a plastic night hat.

01:22:54.650 --> 01:22:58.820
So he zooms around with that all of the time,
and he’s got this plastic sword, and he

01:22:58.820 --> 01:22:59.820
zooms around with that too.

01:22:59.820 --> 01:23:02.090
So you think what’s he up to?

01:23:02.090 --> 01:23:06.541
He’s playing knight, which is kind of weird
in a way.

01:23:06.541 --> 01:23:11.020
Because you’d think why would being a knight
be attractive to a kid?

01:23:11.020 --> 01:23:12.710
We weren’t knights for that long.

01:23:12.710 --> 01:23:14.160
Whatever, it doesn’t really matter.

01:23:14.160 --> 01:23:17.060
He was running around playing knight.

01:23:17.060 --> 01:23:21.400
He goes to sleep and he puts his knight hat
and is sword right beside his bed.

01:23:21.400 --> 01:23:23.410
So fine, I watch that.

01:23:23.410 --> 01:23:26.430
I’m watching what’s going on with them
and I’m figuring out what’s going on in

01:23:26.430 --> 01:23:27.430
the house.

01:23:27.430 --> 01:23:29.810
His mom is worried because he’s having night
terrors.

01:23:29.810 --> 01:23:32.450
Yeah, it’s horrible he wakes up screaming.

01:23:32.450 --> 01:23:34.440
So okay, nighttime comes.

01:23:34.440 --> 01:23:38.920
He wakes up screaming, we’re all sitting
at the breakfast table the next day.

01:23:38.920 --> 01:23:42.270
I said, did you dream about anything?

01:23:42.270 --> 01:23:43.340
He said, yeah!

01:23:43.340 --> 01:23:50.570
He got right into this dream and he said okay,
this is what happened: I was out in a field

01:23:50.570 --> 01:23:53.650
and all of these little dwarfs were around
me.

01:23:53.650 --> 01:23:57.310
They only came up to my knees but they had
big beaks, they didn’t have any arms, but

01:23:57.310 --> 01:23:59.400
they had big beaks.

01:23:59.400 --> 01:24:02.120
They were covered with hair and grease, so
they were all greased down.

01:24:02.120 --> 01:24:06.550
There was a cross-shave at the top of their
head, and wherever I went these beaked dwarfs

01:24:06.550 --> 01:24:10.680
would jump at me with their feet and bite
me.

01:24:10.680 --> 01:24:13.400
They’re everywhere!

01:24:13.400 --> 01:24:17.260
Everyone stops eating breakfast to look at
this kid, thinking, wow no wonder why you’re

01:24:17.260 --> 01:24:19.380
screaming man.

01:24:19.380 --> 01:24:25.010
Then he said, yeah, and it was worse than
that because there was smoke and at the back

01:24:25.010 --> 01:24:29.340
of the dwarfs there was this dragon and the
dragon was breathing out smoke and fire and

01:24:29.340 --> 01:24:31.150
the smoke and fire would turn into the dwarfs.

01:24:31.150 --> 01:24:33.830
Oh my God, what do you do about that?

01:24:33.830 --> 01:24:37.910
Wiping out some dwarfs, who cares, but the
dragon will just breathe up some more.

01:24:37.910 --> 01:24:39.900
That’s life man.

01:24:39.900 --> 01:24:46.510
I’ve got this excellent picture, let me
show it to you because it’s worth finding,

01:24:46.510 --> 01:25:14.010
even though it’s going to interrupt my story
a little bit.

01:25:14.010 --> 01:25:16.390
Well I’m not going to find it because it
will take too long, but I’ll tell you what

01:25:16.390 --> 01:25:17.390
it is.

01:25:17.390 --> 01:25:19.670
It’s a Greek amphora.

01:25:19.670 --> 01:25:25.350
You know amphora, it’s like a vase, and
people used to keep wine in them.

01:25:25.350 --> 01:25:29.810
It’s painted on like a cartoon, it’s sort
of black and white.

01:25:29.810 --> 01:25:33.630
It’s got this hero, who I believe is Hercules.

01:25:33.630 --> 01:25:37.080
Hercules is facing this snake, and it’s
a really cool snake.

01:25:37.080 --> 01:25:40.810
So first of all it’s tail is curled in a
perfect circle.

01:25:40.810 --> 01:25:47.930
If you look at dragons and snakes in mythology,
their tales are often curled in a circle.

01:25:47.930 --> 01:25:51.520
It means something like infinity.

01:25:51.520 --> 01:25:53.570
Then there are all these snakes – it’s
a hydra.

01:25:53.570 --> 01:25:56.040
It’s a snake with eight heads.

01:25:56.040 --> 01:25:59.580
Then there’s Hercules with his sword – well,
what’s the problem with the hydra?

01:25:59.580 --> 01:26:04.790
You cut off one head and eight more heads
grow.

01:26:04.790 --> 01:26:12.000
Quit cutting off heads – it’s a good piece
of foreign policy advice for the middle east.

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:13.360
The hydras keep growing.

01:26:13.360 --> 01:26:16.370
Okay, so cutting off heads isn’t going to
be of any utility.

01:26:16.370 --> 01:26:21.210
Here’s what the story is saying: no matter
how many problems you solve there’s going

01:26:21.210 --> 01:26:24.670
to be a bunch more problems and it’s even
worse than that.

01:26:24.670 --> 01:26:28.489
If you have a problem and you solve it that’s
going to lead to more problems.

01:26:28.489 --> 01:26:30.380
So even the solution is a problem.

01:26:30.380 --> 01:26:32.980
That’s the law of unexpected consequences.

01:26:32.980 --> 01:26:36.060
That’s why automobiles have destroyed the
atmosphere.

01:26:36.060 --> 01:26:40.770
Everybody thought an automobile is for getting
from point A to point B. It turns out it’s

01:26:40.770 --> 01:26:41.770
not.

01:26:41.770 --> 01:26:45.550
It’s for turning the world’s holes into
jungles.

01:26:45.550 --> 01:26:47.270
We didn’t know that.

01:26:47.270 --> 01:26:50.270
So that’s an unexpected consequence.

01:26:50.270 --> 01:26:54.510
So anyways, the kid is faced with this horrible
conundrum.

01:26:54.510 --> 01:26:55.510
What am I going to do?

01:26:55.510 --> 01:26:58.610
I’ve got these stupid dwarfs and then there’s
this dragon.

01:26:58.610 --> 01:27:03.530
So I said, what could you do about that?

01:27:03.530 --> 01:27:07.130
Now that’s called a loaded question and
it would be inadmissible in a court of law

01:27:07.130 --> 01:27:14.580
in a sense because it’s a question – but
it isn’t because I’m telling him something.

01:27:14.580 --> 01:27:18.489
You could do something about that.

01:27:18.489 --> 01:27:19.890
Well that’s a hell of a theory.

01:27:19.890 --> 01:27:23.070
Well yeah, I should just lay down and let
the dwarfs eat me.

01:27:23.070 --> 01:27:25.320
No, no you could do something about it, I
said.

01:27:25.320 --> 01:27:26.380
What could you do?

01:27:26.380 --> 01:27:32.920
Then he said, I’d put my hat on, I’d get
my sword, then I’d go get my dad and we’d

01:27:32.920 --> 01:27:33.920
go up to the dragon.

01:27:33.920 --> 01:27:38.050
I would jump on his head and then I’d poke
both his eyes out with my sword and then I’d

01:27:38.050 --> 01:27:42.320
go right down to his stomach to the place
where the fire comes out and I’d cut a piece

01:27:42.320 --> 01:27:45.640
off of that and I’d use it as a shield.

01:27:45.640 --> 01:27:48.050
And I thought, “right on, kid!

01:27:48.050 --> 01:27:49.050
You got it.”

01:27:49.050 --> 01:27:51.780
It was so cool because he had the whole thing,
eh.

01:27:51.780 --> 01:27:53.469
That’s why he was running around playing
knight.

01:27:53.469 --> 01:27:59.210
He’d almost got it, and all I had to do
was drop – there’s this fifth chemical

01:27:59.210 --> 01:28:01.880
phenomena called a super-saturated solution.

01:28:01.880 --> 01:28:02.920
It’s kind of cool.

01:28:02.920 --> 01:28:10.270
So if you take - water can only dissolve so
much sugar until the sugar starts to crystallize

01:28:10.270 --> 01:28:14.800
out.

01:28:14.800 --> 01:28:22.820
If you really slowly cool down then water
and you don’t tap it there’s no impurities.

01:28:22.820 --> 01:28:27.730
You can get the solution super saturated which
means, weirdly enough, it holds more sugar

01:28:27.730 --> 01:28:29.180
than it can.

01:28:29.180 --> 01:28:34.540
It’s like it forgets to crystallize or maybe
it needs a little impurity or shock or something

01:28:34.540 --> 01:28:37.470
to get it going, but it’s like it forgets
to crystallize.

01:28:37.470 --> 01:28:40.167
So then if you take a little crystal of sugar
and you drop it in, it’s like it goes “sound”

01:28:40.167 --> 01:28:44.040
and instantly it’s all crystals.

01:28:44.040 --> 01:28:49.300
So that’s what happened to this kid: he
was there, he was ready, he had to answer,

01:28:49.300 --> 01:28:54.720
and all I had to do was say you could do something
about this and “poof!”

01:28:54.720 --> 01:28:55.790
instant hero myth.

01:28:55.790 --> 01:29:01.870
The cool thing is no more night terrors.

01:29:01.870 --> 01:29:05.000
So you get the picture, it’s very, very
cool.

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:09.600
Alright so, back to our discussion.

01:29:09.600 --> 01:29:24.460
Now, alright so you’ve got the brain here.

01:29:24.460 --> 01:29:37.740
This is the brain as conceptualized by Alexander
Luria, who was Russia’s most famous neuropsychologist.

01:29:37.740 --> 01:29:42.390
So basically he said that there’s a bunch
of different ways you can divide up the brain.

01:29:42.390 --> 01:29:46.660
It depends on what you want, which is an interesting
way of thinking about it.

01:29:46.660 --> 01:29:50.700
Because you might say well how should you
divide up the world and the answer is it depends

01:29:50.700 --> 01:29:52.239
on what you want.

01:29:52.239 --> 01:29:57.760
It depends on some degree of the world, but
it depends even more on what you want.

01:29:57.760 --> 01:30:02.889
So one of the things Luria said was if you
go from the back to the front of the brain

01:30:02.889 --> 01:30:07.550
– the front’s the grey part here – what
you see is, roughly speaking, the back half

01:30:07.550 --> 01:30:12.700
of the brain does sensory processing, especially
visual processing, and the front half of the

01:30:12.700 --> 01:30:14.410
brain does motor processing.

01:30:14.410 --> 01:30:18.980
Okay, and so if you look at the back of the
brain the sensory unit there, you see there’s

01:30:18.980 --> 01:30:21.190
an auditory area and a visual area.

01:30:21.190 --> 01:30:24.730
What’s cool is those overlap to some degree.

01:30:24.730 --> 01:30:29.750
So there’s some hypothesis that the place
where the sensory systems overlap are the

01:30:29.750 --> 01:30:34.930
parts that are responsible for your experience
of a unified perceptual field.

01:30:34.930 --> 01:30:39.320
So here’s an example: imagine the visual
cortex and the auditory cortex overlap in

01:30:39.320 --> 01:30:40.320
once place.

01:30:40.320 --> 01:30:45.840
Okay, so it would sort of be here, about there
on the left side.

01:30:45.840 --> 01:30:48.489
That’s the part you use for silent reading.

01:30:48.489 --> 01:30:50.489
Isn’t that cool?

01:30:50.489 --> 01:30:52.550
It means your using your eyes as ears.

01:30:52.550 --> 01:30:56.390
The way you do that is you use the overlap
between the visual and the auditory cortex.

01:30:56.390 --> 01:31:00.390
It’s so cool, you can use your eyes as ears.

01:31:00.390 --> 01:31:03.440
So the senses aren’t as separate as people
think.

01:31:03.440 --> 01:31:07.390
I used to wear glasses and I couldn’t hear
what people were saying when I wasn’t wearing

01:31:07.390 --> 01:31:08.390
them.

01:31:08.390 --> 01:31:10.820
The reason for that is I wasn’t watching
their lips.

01:31:10.820 --> 01:31:14.680
So a lot of what I was hearing in language
processing was the expression on their face

01:31:14.680 --> 01:31:15.980
and the movement of their lips.

01:31:15.980 --> 01:31:18.490
I take off my glasses, and I’m deaf.

01:31:18.490 --> 01:31:21.440
So anyways, that’s the sensory unit, half
of the brain.

01:31:21.440 --> 01:31:24.690
Most of it’s the visual cortex because we’re
visual creatures.

01:31:24.690 --> 01:31:26.739
The front half is the motor unit.

01:31:26.739 --> 01:31:27.910
Okay, why?

01:31:27.910 --> 01:31:31.219
Well because we proceed and act.

01:31:31.219 --> 01:31:34.230
So it’s the part of the brain that’s responsible
for zipping you around.

01:31:34.230 --> 01:31:36.650
You’ve got voluntary action, right?

01:31:36.650 --> 01:31:43.180
You inhabit a nervous system that enables
you to navigate your way around the world.

01:31:43.180 --> 01:31:44.469
We’re navigators, fundamentally.

01:31:44.469 --> 01:31:48.010
We really are navigators.

01:31:48.010 --> 01:31:51.010
You know ants can navigate by the stars?

01:31:51.010 --> 01:31:52.010
Think about that.

01:31:52.010 --> 01:31:54.530
How the hell can an ant navigate by the stars?

01:31:54.530 --> 01:31:59.590
They figured that out by watching ants figure
out how to get back, and then covering up

01:31:59.590 --> 01:32:03.260
the sky, and then the ants would wander around
not knowing where they were going.

01:32:03.260 --> 01:32:07.070
Yeah there’s lots of things we don’t understand,
I can tell you that.

01:32:07.070 --> 01:32:08.910
So anyways, the motor unit.

01:32:08.910 --> 01:32:11.230
You’ve got the motor strip.

01:32:11.230 --> 01:32:15.810
Now if you touch that with an electrode during
brain surgery then people will either move

01:32:15.810 --> 01:32:20.450
or have the impulse to move and you can map
out how the body is represented in the brain

01:32:20.450 --> 01:32:24.460
by touching that strip with an electrode,
and that was done by Wilmer Penfield at the

01:32:24.460 --> 01:32:25.920
Montreal Neurological Institute.

01:32:25.920 --> 01:32:31.250
It was a major move forward in the understanding
of the brain and he did that on epileptics

01:32:31.250 --> 01:32:35.560
before surgery, because he didn’t want to
take out parts of the brain that were necessary

01:32:35.560 --> 01:32:37.730
so he was trying to figure out what they were
doing.

01:32:37.730 --> 01:32:42.020
So that’s the part that enables you to act
voluntarily, and in front of that there’s

01:32:42.020 --> 01:32:44.360
the premotor strip.

01:32:44.360 --> 01:32:47.030
In front of that there’s the prefrontal
cortex.

01:32:47.030 --> 01:32:53.710
Now, what’s cool is that the premotor strip
and the prefrontal cortex grew out of the

01:32:53.710 --> 01:32:56.160
motor strip over the course of evolution.

01:32:56.160 --> 01:32:59.610
So then you might say, well why do we think?

01:32:59.610 --> 01:33:03.320
The answer isn’t so that we can come up
with accurate, objective representations of

01:33:03.320 --> 01:33:04.320
the world.

01:33:04.320 --> 01:33:07.200
The answer is, so that we can plan what to
do.

01:33:07.200 --> 01:33:14.460
What you see, fundamentally, is that as you
move forward in the brain you go from action

01:33:14.460 --> 01:33:16.400
to planning action.

01:33:16.400 --> 01:33:20.230
So by the time you get to the prefrontal cortex,
let’s say the dorsal-lateral prefrontal

01:33:20.230 --> 01:33:24.810
cortex, which is the part of the brain that
you use for abstract thinking, what you’re

01:33:24.810 --> 01:33:33.780
basically doing is conjuring up avatars of
yourself in an imaginary world, running them

01:33:33.780 --> 01:33:38.270
as simulations in your imagination, and the
collective imagination, that’s what stories

01:33:38.270 --> 01:33:42.910
are, running the simulation until the end
to see if you live or die.

01:33:42.910 --> 01:33:45.740
If you die then you don’t implement the
simulation.

01:33:45.740 --> 01:33:49.270
If you live and thrive then you do implement
the situation.

01:33:49.270 --> 01:33:57.200
So – who was it – Carl Popper, philosopher
of science said, the reason we think is so

01:33:57.200 --> 01:34:00.200
we can let our thoughts die instead of us.

01:34:00.200 --> 01:34:03.290
Right, that’s smart.

01:34:03.290 --> 01:34:06.640
That also ties into the death and rebirth
idea, right?

01:34:06.640 --> 01:34:11.100
Are you going to die, or are you going to
let your avatars die?

01:34:11.100 --> 01:34:17.710
One way of thinking about that is that your
current self is just an avatar.

01:34:17.710 --> 01:34:21.490
Now if you understand that, that means you
also understand the relationship between the

01:34:21.490 --> 01:34:25.210
Jungian self and the ego.

01:34:25.210 --> 01:34:28.580
The ego is an avatar, the self is the thing.

01:34:28.580 --> 01:34:33.600
Now I don’t know if you know this, but the
word avatar is actually a theological term.

01:34:33.600 --> 01:34:36.270
It’s from Sand script.

01:34:36.270 --> 01:34:39.720
An avatar is the form that a God takes on
earth.

01:34:39.720 --> 01:34:43.969
It’s pretty cool that that turned into the
term for the thing you use in a video game.

01:34:43.969 --> 01:34:48.920
That’s your little, disposable self.

01:34:48.920 --> 01:34:52.050
You throw it out there in the world and it
can live or die, and you’re back there like

01:34:52.050 --> 01:34:54.880
God just being eternal all along the way.

01:34:54.880 --> 01:34:58.050
So, that’s a very, very weird thing.

01:34:58.050 --> 01:35:01.090
Anyways, even before we had video games we
were doing that.

01:35:01.090 --> 01:35:07.239
We had fiction, we had stories, we had imagination,
and it’s decoupled from our motor systems.

01:35:07.239 --> 01:35:13.780
So we can implement these hypothetical instances
of ourselves before we implement them.

01:35:13.780 --> 01:35:15.500
That’s kind of how we fight Hydras.

01:35:15.500 --> 01:35:18.250
Okay, so you have eight snakes, what do you
do about that?

01:35:18.250 --> 01:35:20.469
You have eight potential selves.

01:35:20.469 --> 01:35:25.050
You multiply potential selves just as fast
as you multiply snakes.

01:35:25.050 --> 01:35:28.840
That’s what evolution does, right?

01:35:28.840 --> 01:35:32.530
Let’s say you’ve got a mongoose.

01:35:32.530 --> 01:35:36.640
Mongoose like to eat snakes, they’re really
good at it.

01:35:36.640 --> 01:35:37.640
They can eat cobras.

01:35:37.640 --> 01:35:38.640
Go Mongoose!

01:35:38.640 --> 01:35:41.890
So you think, well a mongoose gets killed
by a cobra.

01:35:41.890 --> 01:35:45.570
Well that’s not a very good mongoose but
that doesn’t matter because the mongoose

01:35:45.570 --> 01:35:49.670
are generating all sorts of mongoose, and
one of them is going to be able to kill the

01:35:49.670 --> 01:35:50.670
snake.

01:35:50.670 --> 01:35:52.540
That’s all that really matters.

01:35:52.540 --> 01:35:58.190
There’s a very funny mouse that lives in
the desert in Arizona.

01:35:58.190 --> 01:36:01.699
I like this mouse a lot, and it jumps.

01:36:01.699 --> 01:36:04.890
It’s so cool, this mouse, it feeds on scorpions.

01:36:04.890 --> 01:36:07.680
How the hell did it learn to do that?

01:36:07.680 --> 01:36:12.400
Anyways, it has to teach its young to eat
scorpions, and its quite immune from scorpion

01:36:12.400 --> 01:36:14.530
venom, which is quite helpful.

01:36:14.530 --> 01:36:19.570
Still it goes out – it’s like you going
out to wrestle a blank crocodile – it’s

01:36:19.570 --> 01:36:22.760
like a scorpion is a big thing compared to
a mouse.

01:36:22.760 --> 01:36:25.730
The mouse will hop on to the scorpion and
they have this terrible fight, and finally

01:36:25.730 --> 01:36:27.000
the mouse tears it a part.

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:30.739
Then it brings it back and feeds it to its
mice babies.

01:36:30.739 --> 01:36:33.180
Do you know what it does then?

01:36:33.180 --> 01:36:37.050
It goes outside and howls at the moon like
a wolf.

01:36:37.050 --> 01:36:44.630
It sounds like a mouse so it’s really squeaky,
but if you slow it down, you know, which is

01:36:44.630 --> 01:36:49.700
what you have to do if you want to, for example,
hear mouse vocalizations, because they’re

01:36:49.700 --> 01:36:54.190
often much higher than your threshold for
hearing.

01:36:54.190 --> 01:36:59.250
Blank that, to hear a rat’s laugh when you
tickle them, you have to slow down their vocalizations

01:36:59.250 --> 01:37:04.310
because they laugh at ultrasonic frequencies,
so you have to slow down your vocalizations

01:37:04.310 --> 01:37:06.130
to hear them laugh when you tickle them.

01:37:06.130 --> 01:37:10.830
Anyways, these damn mice go out in the desert
at night, after eating a scorpion, and they

01:37:10.830 --> 01:37:12.640
howl at the moon.

01:37:12.640 --> 01:37:15.660
Go mice.

01:37:15.660 --> 01:37:20.949
So anyways, back to the brain here.

01:37:20.949 --> 01:37:24.570
There are all of these terrible monsters being
generated.

01:37:24.570 --> 01:37:29.050
You generate avatars of yourself to cope with
them, and generally used to have to evolve

01:37:29.050 --> 01:37:33.930
to do that, but human beings, being the smart
creatures that we are, generated up an environment

01:37:33.930 --> 01:37:39.340
in the imagination and then populated it with
imaginary representations of ourselves, and

01:37:39.340 --> 01:37:40.880
then tried those out.

01:37:40.880 --> 01:37:43.699
Then we implement the ones that we think are
great.

01:37:43.699 --> 01:37:48.110
Then you might think, well we’ve been doing
that for a very, very, very long time.

01:37:48.110 --> 01:37:52.910
then you might think, maybe we’ve figured
out exactly what thing we should implement,

01:37:52.910 --> 01:37:57.670
then we might say well that’s the savior
figures in mythology.

01:37:57.670 --> 01:38:00.280
That’s what they are.

01:38:00.280 --> 01:38:02.219
What else would they be?

01:38:02.219 --> 01:38:05.280
People have been trying to figure out what
the hell we are forever.

01:38:05.280 --> 01:38:10.840
The fundamental question, what is reality
made of, is not the fundamental question.

01:38:10.840 --> 01:38:15.090
The fundamental question is, how do you act
in the world?

01:38:15.090 --> 01:38:18.510
That’s a whole different way of thinking
about the world, but I think, given that I’m

01:38:18.510 --> 01:38:23.770
a Darwinian, I think it’s the fundamental
question.

01:38:23.770 --> 01:38:29.920
You know, obviously, given what I’ve described
to you so far, you can’t fall in love too

01:38:29.920 --> 01:38:33.090
much with your current self.

01:38:33.090 --> 01:38:34.150
What if it’s wrong?

01:38:34.150 --> 01:38:35.850
Then you should let that sucker die.

01:38:35.850 --> 01:38:41.110
Then you might think, well what part of you
is it that doesn’t die when your avatars

01:38:41.110 --> 01:38:42.110
die.

01:38:42.110 --> 01:38:43.750
Well that’s what Jung called the self.

01:38:43.750 --> 01:38:46.500
Let’s say you undergo a personality transformation.

01:38:46.500 --> 01:38:50.469
There’s the old you, you’re all naïve
and something comes along and just wallops

01:38:50.469 --> 01:38:51.469
you, bang!

01:38:51.469 --> 01:38:52.960
Into the underworld, you fall apart.

01:38:52.960 --> 01:38:53.960
Then, bang!

01:38:53.960 --> 01:38:55.860
There’s a new you.

01:38:55.860 --> 01:38:59.180
Maybe a little battle weary, but wiser.

01:38:59.180 --> 01:39:04.690
Then you know that one gets walloped out and
into the underworld and up you come again.

01:39:04.690 --> 01:39:07.949
Fine, what’s constant across all of those
transformations?

01:39:07.949 --> 01:39:11.470
That’s the core element of the person.

01:39:11.470 --> 01:39:14.480
That’s what Jung called the self.

01:39:14.480 --> 01:39:21.989
Brilliant, it’s so smart.

